arrays/map.html.body:
Map
The Array.prototype.map() method iterates over an array and modifies its elements using a callback function. The callback function will then be applied to each element of the array.
‡§è‡§∞‡•ç‡§∞‡•á .‡§™‡•ç‡§∞‡•ã‡§ü‡•ã‡§§‡§ø‡§ü‡§æ‡§Ø‡§™‡§ø‡§™‡•§ Mage ‡§µ‡§ø‡§ß‡§ø ‡§è‡§ï ‡§è‡§∞‡•á‡§Æ‡§æ ‡§™‡•Å‡§®‡§∞‡§æ‡§µ‡•É‡§§‡•ç‡§§‡§ø ‡§ó‡§∞‡•ç‡§¶‡§õ ‡§∞ ‡§Ø‡§∏‡§ï‡•ã ‡§§‡§§‡•ç‡§µ‡§π‡§∞‡•Ç‡§≤‡§æ‡§à ‡§ï‡§≤‡§¨‡•ç‡§Ø‡§æ‡§ï ‡§ï‡§æ‡§∞‡•ç‡§Ø ‡§™‡•ç‡§∞‡§Ø‡•ã‡§ó ‡§ó‡§∞‡•á‡§∞ ‡§™‡§∞‡§ø‡§Æ‡§æ‡§∞‡•ç‡§ú‡§® ‡§ó‡§∞‡•ç‡§¶‡§õ‡•§ ‡§ï‡§≤‡§¨‡•ç‡§Ø‡§æ‡§ï ‡§™‡•ç‡§∞‡§ï‡§æ‡§∞‡•ç‡§Ø ‡§§‡•ç‡§Ø‡§∏‡§™‡§õ‡§ø ‡§è‡§∞‡•ç‡§∞‡•á‡§ï‡•ã ‡§™‡•ç‡§∞‡§§‡•ç‡§Ø‡•á‡§ï ‡§§‡§§‡•ç‡§µ‡§Æ‡§æ ‡§≤‡§æ‡§ó‡•Ç ‡§π‡•Å‡§®‡•á‡§õ‡•§
Here's the syntax for using map:
‡§Ø‡§π‡§æ‡§Å anterax k` ‡§®‡§ï‡•ç‡§∂‡§æ ‡§™‡•ç‡§∞‡§Ø‡•ã‡§ó‡§ï‡•ã ‡§≤‡§æ‡§ó‡§ø ‡§õ:
let newArray = oldArray.map(function(element, index, array) {
  // element: current element being processed in the array
  // index: index of the current element being processed in the array
  // array: the array map was called upon
  // Return element to be added to newArray
});

For example, let's say you have an array of numbers and you want to create a new array that doubles the values of the numbers in the original array. You could do this using map like this:
‡§â‡§¶‡§æ‡§π‡§∞‡§£‡§ï‡§æ ‡§≤‡§æ‡§ó‡§ø, ‡§Æ‡§æ‡§®‡•å‡§Ç ‡§ï‡§ø ‡§§‡§™‡§æ‡§à‡§∏‡§Å‡§ó ‡§®‡§Æ‡•ç‡§¨‡§∞‡§π‡§∞‡•Ç‡§ï‡•ã ‡§è‡§∞‡•ç‡§∞‡•á ‡§õ ‡§∞ ‡§§‡§™‡§æ‡§á‡§Å ‡§®‡§Ø‡§æ‡§Å ‡§è‡§∞‡•ç‡§∞‡•á ‡§∏‡§ø‡§∞‡•ç‡§ú‡§®‡§æ ‡§ó‡§∞‡•ç‡§® ‡§ö‡§æ‡§π‡§æ‡§®‡•Å‡§π‡•Å‡§®‡•ç‡§õ ‡§ú‡•Å‡§® ‡§Æ‡•Ç‡§≤ ‡§è‡§∞‡•ç‡§∞‡•á‡§ï‡•ã ‡§Æ‡§æ‡§®‡§π‡§∞‡•Ç‡§ï‡•ã ‡§Æ‡§æ‡§® ‡§°‡§¨‡§≤‡•ç‡§∏ ‡§ó‡§∞‡•ç‡§¶‡§õ‡•§ ‡§§‡§™‡§æ‡§à‡§Ç ‡§Ø‡§∏‡§≤‡§æ‡§à ‡§ú‡§∏‡•ç‡§§‡•à `‡§®‡§ï‡•ç‡§∂‡§æ‡§ï‡•ã ‡§ú‡§∏‡•ç‡§§‡•à ‡§™‡•ç‡§∞‡§Ø‡•ã‡§ó ‡§ó‡§∞‡•ç‡§® ‡§∏‡§ï‡•ç‡§®‡•Å‡§π‡•Å‡§®‡•ç‡§õ:
const numbers = [2, 4, 6, 8];

const doubledNumbers = numbers.map(number => number * 2);

console.log(doubledNumbers);

// Result: [4, 8, 12, 16]

You can also use the arrow function syntax to define the function passed to map:
‡§§‡§™‡§æ‡§à‡§Ç ‡§è‡§∞‡•ç‡§∞‡•ã ‡§™‡•ç‡§∞‡§ï‡§æ‡§∞‡•ç‡§Ø ‡§∏‡§ø‡§®‡•ç‡§ü‡•ç‡§Ø‡§æ‡§ï‡•ç‡§∏ ‡§™‡§®‡§ø ‡§™‡•ç‡§∞‡§Ø‡•ã‡§ó ‡§ó‡§∞‡•ç‡§® ‡§∏‡§ï‡•ç‡§®‡•Å‡§π‡•Å‡§®‡•á‡§õ ‡§™‡•ç‡§∞‡§ï‡§æ‡§∞‡•ç‡§Ø ‡§™‡§∞‡§ø‡§≠‡§æ‡§∑‡§ø‡§§ ‡§ó‡§∞‡•ç‡§® `‡§®‡§ï‡•ç‡§∂‡§æ‡§ï‡•ã ‡§≤‡§æ‡§ó‡§ø:
let doubledNumbers = numbers.map((number) => {

  Dotherdumbumers = ‡§∏‡§Ç‡§ñ‡•ç‡§Ø‡§æ (‡§∏‡§Ç‡§ñ‡•ç‡§Ø‡§æ) =>
  return number * 2;

 ‡§∞‡§ø‡§ü‡§∞‡•ç‡§® ‡§®‡§Æ‡•ç‡§¨‡§∞ * 2;});


or
‡§Ö‡§•‡§µ‡§æ
let doubledNumbers = numbers.map(number => number * 2);

The map() method doesn't execute function for empty elements and doesn't change the original array.
‡§®‡§ï‡•ç‡§∂‡§æ () ‡§µ‡§ø‡§ß‡§ø ‡§ñ‡§æ‡§≤‡•Ä ‡§§‡§§‡•ç‡§µ‡§π‡§∞‡•Ç‡§ï‡•ã ‡§≤‡§æ‡§ó‡§ø ‡§ï‡§æ‡§∞‡•ç‡§Ø‡§æ‡§®‡•ç‡§µ‡§Ø‡§® ‡§ó‡§∞‡•ç‡§¶‡•à‡§® ‡§∞ ‡§Æ‡•Ç‡§≤ ‡§è‡§∞‡•ç‡§∞‡•á ‡§™‡§∞‡§ø‡§µ‡§∞‡•ç‡§§‡§® ‡§π‡•Å‡§Å‡§¶‡•à‡§®‡•§

arrays/spread.html.body:
Spread
‡§´‡•à‡§≤‡§®‡•á
An array or object can be quickly copied into another array or object by using the Spread Operator (...). It allows an iterable such as an array to be expanded in places where zero or more arguments (for function calls) or elements (for array literals) are expected, or an object expression to be expanded in places where zero or more key-value pairs (for object literals) are expected.
‡§è‡§ï ‡§è‡§∞‡•ç‡§∞‡•á ‡§µ‡§æ ‡§µ‡§∏‡•ç‡§§‡•Å‡§≤‡§æ‡§à ‡§ö‡§æ‡§Å‡§°‡•à ‡§Ö‡§∞‡•ç‡§ï‡•ã ‡§è‡§∞‡•ç‡§∞‡•á ‡§µ‡§æ ‡§µ‡§∏‡•ç‡§§‡•Å‡§Æ‡§æ ‡§µ‡§ø‡§∏‡•ç‡§§‡•É‡§§ ‡§Ö‡§™‡§∞‡•á‡§ü‡§∞ ‡§™‡•ç‡§∞‡§Ø‡•ã‡§ó ‡§ó‡§∞‡•á‡§∞ ‡§™‡•ç‡§∞‡§§‡§ø‡§≤‡§ø‡§™‡§ø ‡§ó‡§∞‡•ç‡§® ‡§∏‡§ï‡§ø‡§®‡•ç‡§õ (...)‡•§ ‡§Ø‡§∏‡§≤‡•á ‡§è‡§∞‡•ç‡§∞‡•ã‡§≤‡§æ‡§à ‡§è‡§ï ‡§è‡§∞‡•ç‡§∞‡•ã‡§≤‡•á ‡§µ‡§ø‡§∏‡•ç‡§§‡§æ‡§∞ ‡§ó‡§∞‡•ç‡§® ‡§Ö‡§®‡•Å‡§Æ‡§§‡§ø ‡§¶‡§ø‡§®‡•ç‡§õ ‡§ú‡§π‡§æ‡§Å ‡§∂‡•Ç‡§®‡•ç‡§Ø ‡§µ‡§æ ‡§Ö‡§ß‡§ø‡§ï ‡§§‡§∞‡•ç‡§ï‡§π‡§∞‡•Ç (‡§™‡•ç‡§∞‡§ï‡§æ‡§∞‡•ç‡§Ø ‡§ï‡§≤‡§π‡§∞‡•Ç‡§ï‡•ã ‡§≤‡§æ‡§ó‡§ø) ‡§µ‡§æ ‡§è‡§∞‡•ç‡§∞‡•á ‡§∂‡§æ‡§¨‡•ç‡§¶‡§ø‡§ï‡§π‡§∞‡•Ç‡§ï‡•ã ‡§≤‡§æ‡§ó‡§ø) ‡§Ö‡§™‡•á‡§ï‡•ç‡§∑‡§ø‡§§ ‡§õ, ‡§µ‡§æ ‡§∂‡•Ç‡§®‡•ç‡§Ø ‡§µ‡§æ ‡§Ö‡§ß‡§ø‡§ï ‡§ï‡•Å‡§û‡•ç‡§ú‡•Ä ‡§Æ‡•Ç‡§≤‡•ç‡§Ø‡§π‡§∞‡•Ç (‡§µ‡§∏‡•ç‡§§‡•Å ‡§∂‡§æ‡§¨‡•ç‡§¶‡§ø‡§ï‡§π‡§∞‡•Ç‡§ï‡•ã ‡§≤‡§æ‡§ó‡§ø) ‡§Ö‡§™‡•á‡§ï‡•ç‡§∑‡§ø‡§§ ‡§õ‡•§
Here are some  examples of it:
‡§Ø‡§π‡§æ‡§Å ‡§ï‡•á‡§π‡§ø ‡§â‡§¶‡§æ‡§π‡§∞‡§£‡§π‡§∞‡•Ç ‡§õ‡§®‡•ç:
let arr = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5]; 

console.log(...arr); 
// Result: 1 2 3 4 5

let arr1;
arr1 = [...arr]; //copies the arr into arr1 

console.log(arr1);    //Result: [1, 2, 3, 4, 5]

arr1 = [6,7];
arr = [...arr,...arr1];

console.log(arr);   //Result: [1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7]

The spread operator only works in modern browsers that support the feature. If you need to support older browsers, you will need to use a transpiler like Babel to convert the spread operator syntax to equivalent ES5 code.
‡§∏‡•ç‡§™‡•ç‡§∞‡•á‡§° ‡§Ö‡§™‡§∞‡•á‡§ü‡§∞‡§≤‡•á ‡§Æ‡§æ‡§§‡•ç‡§∞ ‡§Ü‡§ß‡•Å‡§®‡§ø‡§ï ‡§¨‡•ç‡§∞‡§æ‡§â‡§ú‡§∞‡§Æ‡§æ ‡§ï‡§æ‡§Æ ‡§ó‡§∞‡•ç‡§¶‡§õ ‡§ú‡•Å‡§® ‡§∏‡•Å‡§µ‡§ø‡§ß‡§æ ‡§∏‡§Æ‡§∞‡•ç‡§•‡§® ‡§ó‡§∞‡•ç‡§¶‡§õ‡•§ ‡§Ø‡§¶‡§ø ‡§§‡§™‡§æ‡§à‡§Ç‡§≤‡•á ‡§¨‡•Å‡§¢‡§æ ‡§¨‡•ç‡§∞‡§æ‡§â‡§ú‡§∞‡§π‡§∞‡•Ç‡§≤‡§æ‡§à ‡§∏‡§Æ‡§∞‡•ç‡§•‡§® ‡§ó‡§∞‡•ç‡§® ‡§Ü‡§µ‡§∂‡•ç‡§Ø‡§ï ‡§õ ‡§≠‡§®‡•á, ‡§¨‡§æ‡§¨‡•á‡§≤ ‡§ú‡§∏‡•ç‡§§‡•à ‡§§‡§™‡§æ‡§à‡§Ç‡§≤‡•á ‡§™‡•ç‡§∞‡§∏‡§æ‡§∞‡§£ ‡§Ö‡§™‡§∞‡•á‡§ü‡§∞‡•á‡§ü‡§∞ ‡§∏‡§ø‡§®‡•ç‡§ü‡•ç‡§Ø‡§æ‡§ï‡•ç‡§∏‡§≤‡§æ‡§à ‡§∞‡•Ç‡§™‡§æ‡§®‡•ç‡§§‡§∞‡§£ ‡§ó‡§∞‡•ç‡§® ‡§∞‡•Ç‡§™‡§æ‡§®‡•ç‡§§‡§∞‡§ø‡§§ ‡§∞‡•Ç‡§™‡§Æ‡§æ ‡§è‡§∏‡§™‡•Ä‡§ì ‡§ï‡•ã‡§°‡§Æ‡§æ ‡§∞‡•Ç‡§™‡§æ‡§®‡•ç‡§§‡§∞‡§£ ‡§ó‡§∞‡•ç‡§®‡§ï‡•ã ‡§≤‡§æ‡§ó‡§ø ‡§§‡§™‡§æ‡§à‡§Ç‡§≤‡•á ‡§ü‡•ç‡§∞‡§æ‡§®‡•ç‡§∏‡§™‡•á‡§≤‡§∞ ‡§™‡•ç‡§∞‡§Ø‡•ã‡§ó ‡§ó‡§∞‡•ç‡§®‡•Å‡§™‡§∞‡•ç‡§®‡•á‡§õ‡•§

arrays/shift.html.body:
Shift
shift deletes the first index of that array and moves all indexes to the left. It changes the original array. Here's the syntax for using shift:
`‡§∂‡§ø‡§´‡•ç‡§ü‡§ï‡•ã ‡§™‡§π‡§ø‡§≤‡•ã ‡§∏‡•Ç‡§ö‡§ï‡§æ‡§Ç‡§ï ‡§π‡§ü‡§æ‡§â‡§Å‡§õ ‡§∞ ‡§∏‡§¨‡•à ‡§Ö‡§®‡•Å‡§ï‡•ç‡§∞‡§Æ‡§£‡§ø‡§ï‡§æ‡§π‡§∞‡•Ç‡§≤‡§æ‡§à ‡§¨‡§æ‡§Å‡§Ø‡§æ‡§Æ‡§æ ‡§∏‡§æ‡§∞‡•ç‡§¶‡§õ‡•§ ‡§Ø‡§∏‡§≤‡•á ‡§Æ‡•Ç‡§≤ ‡§è‡§∞‡•ç‡§∞‡•á ‡§™‡§∞‡§ø‡§µ‡§∞‡•ç‡§§‡§® ‡§ó‡§∞‡•ç‡§¶‡§õ‡•§ ‡§Ø‡§π‡§æ‡§Å ‡§∏‡§ø‡§´‡•ç‡§ü‡§®‡§ï‡•ã ‡§™‡•ç‡§∞‡§Ø‡•ã‡§ó‡§ï‡•ã ‡§≤‡§æ‡§ó‡§ø anttance ‡§õ:
array.shift();

For example: 
let array = [1, 2, 3]; 
array.shift(); 

// Result: array = [2,3]

You can also use the shift method in conjunction with a loop to remove all elements from an array. Here's an example of how you might do this:
‡§§‡§™‡§æ‡§à‡§Ç ‡§è‡§∞‡•ç‡§∞‡•á‡§ï‡•ã‡§¨‡§æ‡§ü ‡§∏‡§¨‡•à ‡§§‡§§‡•ç‡§µ‡§π‡§∞‡•Ç ‡§π‡§ü‡§æ‡§â‡§® `‡§∂‡§ø‡§´‡•ç‡§ü‡§ï‡•ã ‡§∏‡§Ç‡§Ø‡•ã‡§ú‡§®‡§ï‡•ã ‡§∏‡§æ‡§• ‡§™‡•ç‡§∞‡§Ø‡•ã‡§ó ‡§ó‡§∞‡•ç‡§® ‡§∏‡§ï‡•ç‡§®‡•Å‡§π‡•Å‡§®‡•á‡§õ‡•§ ‡§Ø‡§π‡§æ‡§Å ‡§ï‡§∏‡§∞‡•Ä ‡§§‡§™‡§æ‡§à‡§Ç ‡§Ø‡•ã ‡§ó‡§∞‡•ç‡§® ‡§∏‡§ï‡•ç‡§®‡•Å‡§π‡•Å‡§®‡•ç‡§õ ‡§ï‡•ã ‡§è‡§ï ‡§â‡§¶‡§æ‡§π‡§∞‡§£ ‡§õ:
while (array.length > 0) {
  array.shift();
}

console.log(array); // Result: []

The shift method only works on arrays, and not on other objects that are similar to arrays such as arguments objects or NodeList objects. If you need to shift elements from one of these types of objects, you will need to convert it to an array first using the Array.prototype.slice() method.
‡§∂‡§ø‡§´‡•ç‡§ü‡§ï‡•ã ‡§µ‡§ø‡§ß‡§ø‡§≤‡•á ‡§ï‡•á‡§µ‡§≤ ‡§è‡§∞‡•ç‡§∞‡•á‡§∏‡§Æ‡§æ ‡§ï‡§æ‡§Æ ‡§ó‡§∞‡•ç‡§¶‡§õ, ‡§∞ ‡§Ö‡§®‡•ç‡§Ø ‡§µ‡§∏‡•ç‡§§‡•Å‡§π‡§∞‡•Ç‡§Æ‡§æ ‡§π‡•ã‡§á‡§® ‡§ú‡•Å‡§® ‡§Ü‡§∞‡•ã‡§™‡§Æ‡§æ ‡§∏‡§Æ‡§æ‡§® ‡§õ‡§®‡•ç ‡§ú‡§∏‡•ç‡§§‡•à ‡§§‡§∞‡•ç‡§ï‡§π‡§∞‡•Ç ‡§µ‡§æ ‡§®‡§æ‡§°‡§ø‡§≤‡§ø‡§∏‡•ç‡§ü ‡§µ‡§∏‡•ç‡§§‡•Å‡§π‡§∞‡•Ç‡•§ ‡§Ø‡§¶‡§ø ‡§§‡§™‡§æ‡§à‡§Ç‡§≤‡§æ‡§à ‡§Ø‡•Ä ‡§Æ‡§ß‡•ç‡§Ø‡•á ‡§ï‡•Å‡§®‡•à ‡§™‡•ç‡§∞‡§ï‡§æ‡§∞‡§ï‡•ã ‡§µ‡§∏‡•ç‡§§‡•Å‡§π‡§∞‡•Ç‡§¨‡§æ‡§ü ‡§§‡§§‡•ç‡§§‡•ç‡§µ‡§π‡§∞‡•Ç ‡§∏‡§æ‡§∞‡•ç‡§®‡•Å ‡§Ü‡§µ‡§∂‡•ç‡§Ø‡§ï ‡§õ ‡§≠‡§®‡•á, ‡§§‡§™‡§æ‡§à‡§Ç‡§≤‡•á ‡§Ø‡§∏‡§≤‡§æ‡§à ‡§è‡§∞‡•ç‡§∞‡•á‡§≤‡§æ‡§à ‡§™‡§π‡§ø‡§≤‡•ã ‡§™‡§ü‡§ï ‡§è‡§∞‡•ç‡§∞‡•á‡•§ ‡§è‡§∞‡•ç‡§∞‡•ã‡§ü‡•ã‡§ü‡§ø‡§™‡•á‡§ü‡§æ‡§ï‡•ã‡§ü‡§ø‡§™‡•á‡§ü‡§ø‡§™ ()‡§µ‡§ø‡§ß‡§ø ‡§™‡•ç‡§∞‡§Ø‡•ã‡§ó ‡§ó‡§∞‡•ç‡§® ‡§Ü‡§µ‡§∂‡•ç‡§Ø‡§ï ‡§™‡§∞‡•ç‡§¶‡§õ‡•§

arrays/pop.html.body:
Pop
The pop method removes the last element from an array and returns that element. This method changes the length of the array.
`‡§™‡§™`` ‡§µ‡§ø‡§ß‡§ø‡§≤‡•á ‡§è‡§∞‡•ç‡§∞‡•á‡§ü‡§¨‡§æ‡§ü ‡§Ö‡§®‡•ç‡§§‡§ø‡§Æ ‡§§‡§§‡•ç‡§µ ‡§π‡§ü‡§æ‡§â‡§Å‡§õ ‡§∞ ‡§§‡•ç‡§Ø‡•ã ‡§§‡§§‡•ç‡§µ ‡§´‡§ø‡§∞‡•ç‡§§‡§æ ‡§ó‡§∞‡•ç‡§¶‡§õ‡•§ ‡§Ø‡§∏ ‡§µ‡§ø‡§ß‡§ø‡§≤‡•á ‡§è‡§∞‡•ç‡§∞‡•á‡§ï‡•ã ‡§≤‡§Æ‡•ç‡§¨‡§æ‡§à ‡§™‡§∞‡§ø‡§µ‡§∞‡•ç‡§§‡§® ‡§ó‡§∞‡•ç‡§¶‡§õ‡•§
Here's the syntax for using pop:
‡§Ø‡§π‡§æ‡§Å ‡§™‡§§‡•ç‡§∞‡•Ä ‡§™‡•ç‡§∞‡§Ø‡•ã‡§ó‡§ï‡•ã ‡§≤‡§æ‡§ó‡§ø anttax ‡§õ:
array.pop();

For example:
‡§â‡§¶‡§æ‡§π‡§∞‡§£ ‡§ï‡•ã ‡§≤‡§æ‡§ó‡•Ä:
let arr = ["one", "two", "three", "four", "five"]; 
arr.pop(); 

console.log(arr); 

// Result: ['one', 'two', 'three', 'four']

You can also use the pop method in conjunction with a loop to remove all elements from an array. Here's an example of how you might do this:
‡§§‡§™‡§æ‡§à‡§Ç ‡§è‡§∞‡•ç‡§∞‡•á‡§¨‡§æ‡§ü ‡§∏‡§¨‡•à ‡§§‡§§‡•ç‡§µ‡§π‡§∞‡•Ç ‡§π‡§ü‡§æ‡§â‡§® ‡§è‡§ï ‡§≤‡•Å‡§™‡§ï‡•ã ‡§∏‡§æ‡§• ‡§™‡§™`` ‡§µ‡§ø‡§ß‡§ø ‡§™‡•ç‡§∞‡§Ø‡•ã‡§ó ‡§ó‡§∞‡•ç‡§® ‡§∏‡§ï‡•ç‡§®‡•Å‡§π‡•Å‡§®‡•á‡§õ‡•§ ‡§Ø‡§π‡§æ‡§Å ‡§ï‡§∏‡§∞‡•Ä ‡§§‡§™‡§æ‡§à‡§Ç ‡§Ø‡•ã ‡§ó‡§∞‡•ç‡§® ‡§∏‡§ï‡•ç‡§®‡•Å‡§π‡•Å‡§®‡•ç‡§õ ‡§ï‡•ã ‡§è‡§ï ‡§â‡§¶‡§æ‡§π‡§∞‡§£ ‡§õ:
while (array.length > 0) {
  array.pop();
}

console.log(array); // Result: []

The pop method only works on arrays, and not on other objects that are similar to arrays such as arguments objects or NodeList objects. If you need to pop elements from one of these types of objects, you will need to convert it to an array first using the Array.prototype.slice() method.\
‡§™‡§™`` ‡§µ‡§ø‡§ß‡§ø‡§≤‡•á ‡§ï‡•á‡§µ‡§≤ ‡§è‡§∞‡•ç‡§∞‡•á‡§∏‡§Æ‡§æ ‡§ï‡§æ‡§Æ ‡§ó‡§∞‡•ç‡§¶‡§õ, ‡§∞ ‡§Ö‡§®‡•ç‡§Ø ‡§µ‡§∏‡•ç‡§§‡•Å‡§π‡§∞‡•Ç‡§Æ‡§æ ‡§ï‡§æ‡§Æ ‡§ó‡§∞‡•ç‡§¶‡•à‡§® ‡§ú‡•Å‡§® ‡§Ü‡§∞‡•ã‡§™‡§Æ‡§æ ‡§∏‡§Æ‡§æ‡§® ‡§§‡§∞‡•ç‡§ï‡§π‡§∞‡•Ç ‡§µ‡§æ ‡§®‡§æ‡§°‡§≤‡§ø‡§∏‡•ç‡§ü ‡§µ‡§∏‡•ç‡§§‡•Å‡§π‡§∞‡•Ç‡•§ ‡§Ø‡§¶‡§ø ‡§§‡§™‡§æ‡§à‡§Ç‡§≤‡§æ‡§à ‡§Ø‡•Ä ‡§Æ‡§ß‡•ç‡§Ø‡•á ‡§ï‡•Å‡§®‡•à ‡§™‡•ç‡§∞‡§ï‡§æ‡§∞‡§ï‡•ã ‡§µ‡§∏‡•ç‡§§‡•Å‡§π‡§∞‡•Ç‡§¨‡§æ‡§ü ‡§™‡•ã‡§™ ‡§§‡§§‡•ç‡§µ‡§π‡§∞‡•Ç ‡§Ü‡§µ‡§∂‡•ç‡§Ø‡§ï ‡§õ ‡§≠‡§®‡•á, ‡§§‡§™‡§æ‡§à‡§Ç‡§≤‡•á ‡§Ø‡§∏‡§≤‡§æ‡§à ‡§è‡§∞‡•ç‡§∞‡•á‡§≤‡§æ‡§à ‡§™‡§π‡§ø‡§≤‡•ã ‡§™‡§ü‡§ï "‡§è‡§∞‡•ç‡§∞‡•á‡§ó‡•ç‡§∞‡§æ‡§ü‡•ã‡§ü‡§ø‡§™‡§ø‡§™‡§≤‡§ø‡§™‡•á‡§°‡§ø‡§™ () ‡§µ‡§ø‡§ß‡§ø ‡§™‡•ç‡§∞‡§Ø‡•ã‡§ó ‡§ó‡§∞‡•ç‡§® ‡§Ü‡§µ‡§∂‡•ç‡§Ø‡§ï ‡§™‡§∞‡•ç‡§¶‡§õ‡•§ ‡§µ‡§ø‡§ß‡§ø‡•§

arrays/join.html.body:
Join
The join method, makes an array turn into a string and joins it all together. It does not change the original array. Here's the syntax for using join:
`‡§∏‡§æ‡§Æ‡•Ç‡§®‡§ï‡•ã ‡§µ‡§ø‡§ß‡§ø, ‡§è‡§∞‡•ç‡§∞‡•á‡§ï‡•ã ‡§Æ‡•ã‡§°‡§≤‡§æ‡§à ‡§∏‡•ç‡§ü‡•ç‡§∞‡§ø in ‡§Æ‡§æ ‡§™‡§∞‡§ø‡§µ‡§∞‡•ç‡§§‡§® ‡§ó‡§∞‡•ç‡§¶‡§õ ‡§∞ ‡§∏‡§¨‡•à ‡§∏‡§Å‡§ó‡•à ‡§Æ‡§ø‡§≤‡•ç‡§õ‡•§ ‡§Ø‡§∏‡§≤‡•á ‡§Æ‡•Ç‡§≤ ‡§è‡§∞‡•á ‡§™‡§∞‡§ø‡§µ‡§∞‡•ç‡§§‡§® ‡§ó‡§∞‡•ç‡§¶‡•à‡§®‡•§ ‡§Ø‡§π‡§æ‡§Å ‡§∏‡§æ‡§Æ‡§ø‡§≤ "‡§ï‡•ã ‡§â‡§™‡§Ø‡•ã‡§ó ‡§ó‡§∞‡•ç‡§® ‡§ï‡•ã ‡§≤‡§æ‡§ó‡•Ä ‡§∏‡§ø‡§®‡•ç‡§ü‡•ç‡§Ø‡§æ‡§ï‡•ç‡§∏ ‡§õ:
array.join([separator]);

The separator argument is optional and specifies the character to be used to separate the elements in the resulting string. If omitted, the array elements are separated with a comma (,).
‡§µ‡§ø‡§≠‡§æ‡§ú‡§ï ‡§§‡§∞‡•ç‡§ï ‡§µ‡•à‡§ï‡§≤‡•ç‡§™‡§ø‡§ï ‡§π‡•ã ‡§∞ ‡§™‡§∞‡§ø‡§£‡§æ‡§Æ‡§∏‡•ç‡§µ‡§∞‡•Ç‡§™ ‡§™‡§∞‡§ø‡§£‡§æ‡§Æ‡§π‡§∞‡•Ç‡§Æ‡§æ ‡§§‡§§‡•ç‡§µ‡§π‡§∞‡•Ç ‡§Ö‡§≤‡§ó ‡§ó‡§∞‡•ç‡§® ‡§ö‡§∞‡§ø‡§§‡•ç‡§∞ ‡§®‡§ø‡§∞‡•ç‡§¶‡§ø‡§∑‡•ç‡§ü ‡§ó‡§∞‡•ç‡§¶‡§õ‡•§ ‡§Ø‡§¶‡§ø ‡§π‡§ü‡§æ‡§á‡§Ø‡•ã ‡§≠‡§®‡•á, ‡§è‡•ç‡§∞‡§æ‡§à ‡§è‡§∞‡•ç‡§∞‡•á ‡§§‡§§‡•ç‡§§‡•ç‡§µ‡§π‡§∞‡•Ç ‡§Ö‡§≤‡•ç‡§™‡§µ‡§ø‡§∞‡§æ‡§Æ‡§∏‡§Å‡§ó ‡§µ‡§ø‡§≠‡§æ‡§ú‡§ø‡§§ ‡§ó‡§∞‡§ø‡§®‡•ç‡§õ (,)‡•§
For example:
‡§â‡§¶‡§æ‡§π‡§∞‡§£ ‡§ï‡•ã ‡§≤‡§æ‡§ó‡•Ä:
let array = ["one", "two", "three", "four"]; 

console.log(array.join(" ")); 

// Result: one two three four

Any separator can be specified but the default one is a comma (,).
‡§ï‡•Å‡§®‡•à ‡§™‡§®‡§ø ‡§µ‡§ø‡§≠‡§æ‡§ú‡§ï ‡§®‡§ø‡§∞‡•ç‡§¶‡§ø‡§∑‡•ç‡§ü ‡§ó‡§∞‡•ç‡§® ‡§∏‡§ï‡§ø‡§®‡•ç‡§õ ‡§§‡§∞ ‡§™‡•Ç‡§∞‡•ç‡§µ‡§®‡§ø‡§∞‡•ç‡§ß‡§æ‡§∞‡§ø‡§§ ‡§è‡§ï ‡§Ö‡§≤‡•ç‡§™‡§µ‡§ø‡§∞‡§æ‡§Æ ‡§π‡•ã (,) `‡•§

In the above example, a space is used as a separator. You can also use join to convert an array-like object (such as an arguments object or a NodeList object) to a string by first converting it to an array using the Array.prototype.slice() method:
‡§Æ‡§æ‡§•‡§ø‡§ï‡•ã ‡§â‡§¶‡§æ‡§π‡§∞‡§£‡§Æ‡§æ, ‡§è‡§ï ‡§†‡§æ‡§â‡§Å ‡§è‡§ï ‡§µ‡§ø‡§≠‡§æ‡§ú‡§ï‡§ï‡•ã ‡§∞‡•Ç‡§™‡§Æ‡§æ ‡§™‡•ç‡§∞‡§Ø‡•ã‡§ó ‡§ó‡§∞‡•Ä‡§®‡•ç‡§õ‡•§ ‡§§‡§™‡§æ‡§à‡§Ç ‡§∏‡§æ‡§Æ‡•Ç‡§π‡§ø‡§ï ‡§∞‡•Ç‡§™‡§Æ‡§æ ‡§è‡§∞‡•ç‡§∞‡•á-‡§ú‡§∏‡•ç‡§§‡•à ‡§µ‡§∏‡•ç‡§§‡•Å‡§π‡§∞‡•Ç ‡§∞‡•Ç‡§™‡§æ‡§®‡•ç‡§§‡§∞‡§£ ‡§ó‡§∞‡•ç‡§® ‡§∏‡§ï‡•ç‡§®‡•Å‡§π‡•Å‡§®‡•á‡§õ (‡§ú‡§∏‡•ç‡§§‡•à ‡§§‡§∞‡•ç‡§ï ‡§µ‡§∏‡•ç‡§§‡•Å‡§π‡§∞‡•Ç ‡§µ‡§æ ‡§è‡§ï ‡§§‡§∞‡•ç‡§ï ‡§µ‡§∏‡•ç‡§§‡•Å ‡§µ‡§æ ‡§è‡§ï ‡§§‡§∞‡•ç‡§ï ‡§µ‡§∏‡•ç‡§§‡•Å ‡§µ‡§æ ‡§è‡§ï ‡§§‡§∞‡•ç‡§ï ‡§µ‡§∏‡•ç‡§§‡•Å ‡§µ‡§æ ‡§è‡§ï ‡§§‡§∞‡•ç‡§ï ‡§µ‡§∏‡•ç‡§§‡•Å ‡§µ‡§æ ‡§è‡§ï ‡§§‡§∞‡•ç‡§ï ‡§µ‡§∏‡•ç‡§§‡•Å ‡§µ‡§æ ‡§è‡§ï ‡§§‡§∞‡•ç‡§ï ‡§µ‡§∏‡•ç‡§§‡•Å) ‡§ï‡•ã ‡§≤‡§æ‡§ó‡•Ä ‡§è‡§∞‡•ç‡§∞‡•á‡§™‡§∞‡•ã‡§ü‡§ø‡§™‡§ø‡§™ .slise.slice () `‡§µ‡§ø‡§ß‡§ø:
function printArguments() {
  console.log(Array.prototype.slice.call(arguments).join(', '));
}

printArguments('a', 'b', 'c'); // Result: "a, b, c"

arrays/length.html.body:
Length
‡§≤‡§Æ‡•ç‡§¨‡§æ‡§á
Arrays have a property called length, and it's pretty much exactly as it sounds, it's the length of the array.
‡§è‡§∞‡•á‡§®‡•ç‡§∏‡§ï‡•ã ‡§è‡§ï ‡§∏‡§Æ‡•ç‡§™‡§§‡•ç‡§§‡•Ä ‡§õ `‡§≤‡§Æ‡•ç‡§¨‡§æ‡§à‡§ï‡•ã ‡§è‡§ï ‡§∏‡§Æ‡•ç‡§™‡§§‡•ç‡§§‡•Ä ‡§õ, ‡§∞ ‡§Ø‡•ã ‡§ß‡•á‡§∞‡•à ‡§∞‡§æ‡§Æ‡•ç‡§∞‡•ã ‡§≤‡§æ‡§ó‡•ç‡§õ, ‡§Ø‡•ã ‡§è‡§∞‡•ç‡§∞‡•á‡§ï‡•ã ‡§≤‡§Æ‡•ç‡§¨‡§æ‡§à ‡§π‡•ã‡•§
let array = [1, 2, 3];

let l = array.length;

// Result: l = 3

The length property also sets the number of elements in an array. For example.
‡§≤‡§Æ‡•ç‡§¨‡§æ‡§à ‡§∏‡§Æ‡•ç‡§™‡§§‡•ç‡§§‡•Ä‡§≤‡•á ‡§è‡§∞‡•ç‡§∞‡•á‡§Æ‡§æ ‡§§‡§§‡•ç‡§µ‡§π‡§∞‡•Ç‡§ï‡•ã ‡§∏‡§Ç‡§ñ‡•ç‡§Ø‡§æ ‡§™‡§®‡§ø ‡§∏‡•á‡§ü ‡§ó‡§∞‡•ç‡§¶‡§õ‡•§ ‡§â‡§¶‡§æ‡§π‡§∞‡§£ ‡§ï‡•ã ‡§≤‡§æ‡§ó‡•Ä‡•§
let fruits = ["Banana", "Orange", "Apple", "Mango"];
fruits.length = 2;

console.log(fruits);
// Result: ['Banana', 'Orange']

You can also use the length property to get the last element of an array by using it as an index. For example:
‡§§‡§™‡§æ‡§à‡§Ç `‡§≤‡§Æ‡•ç‡§¨‡§æ‡§á‡§ï‡•ã ‡§∏‡§Æ‡•ç‡§™‡§§‡•ç‡§§‡•Ä‡§≤‡§æ‡§à ‡§Ö‡§®‡•Å‡§ï‡•ç‡§∞‡§Æ‡§£‡§ø‡§ï‡§æ‡§ï‡•ã ‡§∞‡•Ç‡§™‡§Æ‡§æ ‡§™‡•ç‡§∞‡§Ø‡•ã‡§ó ‡§ó‡§∞‡•á‡§∞ ‡§è‡§∞‡•ç‡§∞‡•á‡§ï‡•ã ‡§Ö‡§®‡•ç‡§§‡§ø‡§Æ ‡§§‡§§‡•ç‡§µ ‡§™‡•ç‡§∞‡§æ‡§™‡•ç‡§§ ‡§ó‡§∞‡•ç‡§® ‡§∏‡§ï‡•ç‡§®‡•Å‡§π‡•Å‡§®‡•á‡§õ‡•§ ‡§â‡§¶‡§æ‡§π‡§∞‡§£ ‡§ï‡•ã ‡§≤‡§æ‡§ó‡•Ä:
console.log(fruits[fruits.length - 1]); // Result: Orange

You can also use the length property to add elements to the end of an array. For example:
‡§§‡§™‡§æ‡§à‡§Ç ‡§è‡§∞‡•ç‡§∞‡•á‡§ï‡•ã ‡§Ö‡§®‡•ç‡§§‡•ç‡§Ø‡§Æ‡§æ ‡§§‡§§‡•ç‡§µ‡§π‡§∞‡•Ç ‡§•‡§™‡•ç‡§® `‡§≤‡§Æ‡•ç‡§¨‡§æ‡§á‡§ï‡•ã ‡§∏‡§Æ‡•ç‡§™‡§§‡•ç‡§§‡§ø ‡§™‡•ç‡§∞‡§Ø‡•ã‡§ó ‡§ó‡§∞‡•ç‡§® ‡§∏‡§ï‡•ç‡§®‡•Å‡§π‡•Å‡§®‡•á‡§õ‡•§ ‡§â‡§¶‡§æ‡§π‡§∞‡§£ ‡§ï‡•ã ‡§≤‡§æ‡§ó‡•Ä:
fruits[fruits.length] = "Pineapple";
console.log(fruits); // Result: ['Banana', 'Orange', 'Pineapple']

The length property is automatically updated when elements are added or removed from the array.
`‡§≤‡§Æ‡•ç‡§¨‡§æ‡§á‡§ï‡•ã ‡§∏‡§Æ‡•ç‡§™‡§§‡•ç‡§§‡§ø ‡§∏‡•ç‡§µ‡§ö‡§æ‡§≤‡§ø‡§§ ‡§∞‡•Ç‡§™‡§Æ‡§æ ‡§Ö‡§™‡§°‡•á‡§ü ‡§π‡•Å‡§®‡•ç‡§õ ‡§ú‡§¨ ‡§§‡§§‡•ç‡§µ‡§π‡§∞‡•Ç ‡§•‡§™‡§ø‡§Ø‡•ã ‡§µ‡§æ ‡§è‡§∞‡•ç‡§∞‡•á‡§¨‡§æ‡§ü ‡§π‡§ü‡§æ‡§á‡§®‡•ç‡§õ‡•§

It's also worth noting that the length property is not a method, so you don't need to use parentheses when accessing it. It's simply a property of the array object that you can access like any other object property.
‡§Ø‡•ã ‡§™‡§®‡§ø ‡§Ø‡§æ‡§¶ ‡§ó‡§∞‡•ç‡§® ‡§≤‡§æ‡§Ø‡§ï‡§ï‡•ã ‡§õ ‡§ï‡§ø `‡§≤‡§Æ‡•ç‡§¨‡§æ‡§à‡§ï‡•ã ‡§∏‡§Æ‡•ç‡§™‡§§‡•ç‡§§‡§ø ‡§è‡§ï ‡§µ‡§ø‡§ß‡§ø ‡§π‡•ã, ‡§§‡•ç‡§Ø‡§∏‡•à‡§≤‡•á ‡§Ø‡§∏‡§ï‡•ã ‡§™‡§π‡•Å‡§Å‡§ö ‡§ó‡§∞‡•ç‡§¶‡§æ ‡§§‡§™‡§æ‡§à‡§≤‡•á ‡§ï‡•ã‡§∑‡•ç‡§†‡§§‡§æ ‡§™‡•ç‡§∞‡§Ø‡•ã‡§ó ‡§ó‡§∞‡•ç‡§®‡•Å‡§™‡§∞‡•ç‡§¶‡•à‡§®‡•§ ‡§Ø‡•ã ‡§ï‡•á‡§µ‡§≤ ‡§è‡§∞‡•ç‡§∞‡•á‡§ï‡•ã ‡§µ‡§∏‡•ç‡§§‡•Å‡§ï‡•ã ‡§∏‡§Æ‡•ç‡§™‡§§‡•ç‡§§‡•Ä ‡§π‡•ã ‡§ú‡•Å‡§® ‡§§‡§™‡§æ‡§à‡§Ç ‡§ï‡•Å‡§®‡•à ‡§Ö‡§®‡•ç‡§Ø ‡§µ‡§∏‡•ç‡§§‡•Å ‡§∏‡§Æ‡•ç‡§™‡§§‡•ç‡§§‡•Ä ‡§ú‡§∏‡•ç‡§§‡•ã ‡§™‡§π‡•Å‡§Å‡§ö ‡§ó‡§∞‡•ç‡§® ‡§∏‡§ï‡•ç‡§®‡•Å‡§π‡•Å‡§®‡•á‡§õ‡•§

arrays/for-each.html.body:
For Each
The forEach method executes a provided function once for each array element. Here's the syntax for using forEach:
‡§™‡•Ç‡§∞‡•ç‡§µ‡§®‡§ø‡§∞‡•ç‡§¶‡•á‡§∂‡§® ‡§µ‡§ø‡§ß‡§ø ‡§™‡•ç‡§∞‡§§‡•ç‡§Ø‡•á‡§ï ‡§è‡§∞‡•ç‡§∞‡•á ‡§§‡§§‡•ç‡§µ‡§ï‡•ã ‡§≤‡§æ‡§ó‡§ø ‡§è‡§ï ‡§™‡•ç‡§∞‡§¶‡§æ‡§® ‡§∏‡§Æ‡•ç‡§™‡§æ‡§¶‡§® ‡§ï‡§æ‡§∞‡•ç‡§Ø‡§æ‡§®‡•ç‡§µ‡§Ø‡§® ‡§ó‡§∞‡•ç‡§¶‡§õ‡•§ ‡§Ø‡§π‡§æ‡§Å sy foresy` ‡§™‡•Ç‡§∞‡•ç‡§µ‡§æ‡§®‡•Å‡§Æ‡§æ‡§®‡§™‡•Ç‡§∞‡•ç‡§µ‡§ï‡•ã ‡§™‡•ç‡§∞‡§Ø‡•ã‡§ó‡§ï‡•ã ‡§≤‡§æ‡§ó‡§ø ‡§õ:
array.forEach(function(element, index, array) {
  // element: current element being processed in the array
  // index: index of the current element being processed in the array
  // array: the array forEach was called upon
});

\
For example, let's say you have an array of numbers and you want to print the double of each number to the console. You could do this using forEach like this:
‡§â‡§¶‡§æ‡§π‡§∞‡§£ ‡§ï‡•ã ‡§≤‡§æ‡§ó‡•Ä, ‡§≠‡§®‡•ç‡§®‡•Å‡§π‡•ã‡§∏‡•ç ‡§ï‡§ø ‡§§‡§™‡§æ‡§á‡§Å‡§∏‡§Å‡§ó ‡§®‡§Æ‡•ç‡§¨‡§∞‡§π‡§∞‡•Ç‡§ï‡•ã ‡§è‡§∞‡•ç‡§∞‡•á ‡§õ ‡§∞ ‡§§‡§™‡§æ‡§à‡§Ç ‡§ï‡§®‡•ç‡§∏‡•ã‡§≤‡§Æ‡§æ ‡§™‡•ç‡§∞‡§§‡•ç‡§Ø‡•á‡§ï ‡§®‡§Æ‡•ç‡§¨‡§∞‡§ï‡•ã ‡§°‡§¨‡§≤ ‡§™‡•ç‡§∞‡§ø‡§®‡•ç‡§ü ‡§ó‡§∞‡•ç‡§® ‡§ö‡§æ‡§π‡§æ‡§®‡•Å‡§π‡•Å‡§®‡•ç‡§õ‡•§ ‡§§‡§™‡§æ‡§à‡§Ç ‡§Ø‡§∏‡§≤‡§æ‡§à ‡§ú‡§∏‡•ç‡§§‡•à `‡§™‡•Ç‡§∞‡•ç‡§µ‡§ï‡•ã ‡§™‡•ç‡§∞‡§Ø‡•ã‡§ó ‡§ó‡§∞‡•á‡§∞ ‡§Ø‡•ã ‡§ó‡§∞‡•ç‡§® ‡§∏‡§ï‡•ç‡§®‡•Å‡§π‡•Å‡§®‡•ç‡§õ:
let numbers = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5];
numbers.forEach(function(number) {
  console.log(number * 2);
});

You can also use the arrow function syntax to define the function passed to forEach:
‡§§‡§™‡§æ‡§à‡§Ç ‡§è‡§∞‡•ç‡§∞‡•ã ‡§™‡•ç‡§∞‡§ï‡§æ‡§∞‡•ç‡§Ø ‡§ë‡§®‡§®‡•ç‡§ü‡•ç‡§Ø‡§æ‡§ï‡•ç‡§∏ ‡§™‡§®‡§ø ‡§™‡•ç‡§∞‡§Ø‡•ã‡§ó ‡§ó‡§∞‡•ç‡§® ‡§∏‡§ï‡•ç‡§®‡•Å‡§π‡•Å‡§®‡•á‡§õ
numbers.forEach((number) => {
  console.log(number * 2);
});

or
‡§Ö‡§•‡§µ‡§æ
numbers.forEach(number => console.log(number * 2));

 forEach does not modify the original array. It simply iterates over the elements of the array and executes the provided function for each element.
& # X20; `‡§Ö‡§ó‡•ç‡§∞‡§ø‡§Æ" ‡§Æ‡•Ç‡§≤ ‡§è‡§∞‡•ç‡§∞‡•á ‡§™‡§∞‡§ø‡§Æ‡§æ‡§∞‡•ç‡§ú‡§® ‡§ó‡§∞‡•ç‡§¶‡•à‡§®‡•§ ‡§Ø‡•ã ‡§è‡§∞‡•ç‡§∞‡•á‡§ï‡§æ ‡§§‡§§‡•ç‡§µ‡§π‡§∞‡•Ç‡§Æ‡§æ ‡§Æ‡§æ‡§§‡•ç‡§∞ ‡§™‡•Å‡§®‡§∞‡§æ‡§µ‡§≤‡•ã‡§ï‡§® ‡§ó‡§∞‡•ç‡§¶‡§õ ‡§∞ ‡§™‡•ç‡§∞‡§§‡•ç‡§Ø‡•á‡§ï ‡§§‡§§‡•ç‡§µ‡§ï‡•ã ‡§≤‡§æ‡§ó‡§ø ‡§™‡•ç‡§∞‡§¶‡§æ‡§® ‡§ó‡§∞‡•ç‡§®‡•á ‡§ï‡§æ‡§∞‡•ç‡§Ø ‡§ï‡§æ‡§∞‡•ç‡§Ø‡§æ‡§®‡•ç‡§µ‡§Ø‡§® ‡§ó‡§∞‡•ç‡§¶‡§õ‡•§
The forEach() method is not executed for the empty statment.
‡§´‡•ã‡§∞‡§ö () ‡§µ‡§ø‡§ß‡§ø ‡§ñ‡§æ‡§≤‡•Ä ‡§ï‡§•‡§®‡§ï‡•ã ‡§≤‡§æ‡§ó‡§ø ‡§ï‡§æ‡§∞‡•ç‡§Ø‡§æ‡§®‡•ç‡§µ‡§Ø‡§® ‡§ó‡§∞‡§ø‡§è‡§ï‡•ã ‡§õ‡•à‡§®‡•§

loops/while.html.body:
While
‡§µ‡§π‡§æ‡§á‡§≤
While Loops repetitively execute a block of code as long as a specified condition is true.
‡§µ‡§π‡§æ‡§á‡§≤ ‡§≤‡•Ç‡§™‡§π‡§∞‡•Ç‡§≤‡•á ‡§®‡§ø‡§∞‡•ç‡§¶‡§ø‡§∑‡•ç‡§ü ‡§ó‡§∞‡§ø‡§è‡§ï‡•ã ‡§Ö‡§µ‡§∏‡•ç‡§•‡§æ ‡§∏‡§§‡•ç‡§Ø ‡§≠‡§è‡§∏‡§Æ‡•ç‡§Æ ‡§ï‡•ã‡§°‡§ï‡•ã ‡§¨‡•ç‡§≤‡§ï ‡§™‡•Å‡§®‡§∞‡§æ‡§µ‡•É‡§§‡•ç‡§§‡§ø ‡§∞‡•Ç‡§™‡§Æ‡§æ ‡§ï‡§æ‡§∞‡•ç‡§Ø‡§æ‡§®‡•ç‡§µ‡§Ø‡§® ‡§ó‡§∞‡•ç‡§¶‡§õ‡•§
while (condition) {
  // do it as long as condition is true
}

For example, the loop in this example will repetitively execute its block of code as long as the variable i is less than 5:
‡§â‡§¶‡§æ‡§π‡§∞‡§£‡§ï‡§æ ‡§≤‡§æ‡§ó‡§ø, ‡§µ‡§π‡§æ‡§á‡§≤ ‡§≤‡•Ç‡§™‡§≤‡•á ‡§Ø‡§∏‡§ï‡•ã ‡§ï‡•ã‡§°‡§ï‡•ã ‡§¨‡•ç‡§≤‡§ï‡§≤‡§æ‡§à ‡§™‡•Å‡§®‡§∞‡§æ‡§µ‡•É‡§§‡•ç‡§§‡§ø ‡§∞‡•Ç‡§™‡§Æ‡§æ ‡§ï‡§æ‡§∞‡•ç‡§Ø‡§æ‡§®‡•ç‡§µ‡§Ø‡§® ‡§ó‡§∞‡•ç‡§®‡•á‡§õ ‡§ú‡§¨‡§∏‡§Æ‡•ç‡§Æ ‡§ö‡§∞ ‡§Æ ‡•´ ‡§≠‡§®‡•ç‡§¶‡§æ ‡§ï‡§Æ ‡§õ:
var i = 0,
  x = "";
while (i 
Be careful to avoid infinite looping if the condition is always true!
‡§Ø‡§¶‡§ø ‡§Ö‡§µ‡§∏‡•ç‡§•‡§æ ‡§∏‡§ß‡•à‡§Ç ‡§∏‡§æ‡§Å‡§ö‡•ã ‡§õ ‡§≠‡§®‡•á ‡§Ö‡§®‡§®‡•ç‡§§ ‡§≤‡•Ç‡§™‡§ø‡§ô‡§¨‡§æ‡§ü ‡§ú‡•ã‡§ó‡§ø‡§® ‡§π‡•ã‡§∏‡§ø‡§Ø‡§æ‡§∞ ‡§π‡•Å‡§®‡•Å‡§π‡•ã‡§∏‡•ç!

objects/mutable.html.body:
Mutable
The difference between objects and primitive values is that we can change objects, whereas primitive values are immutable.
‡§µ‡§∏‡•ç‡§§‡•Å‡§π‡§∞‡•Ç ‡§∞ ‡§Ü‡§¶‡§ø‡§Æ ‡§Æ‡•Ç‡§≤‡•ç‡§Ø‡§π‡§∞‡•Ç ‡§¨‡•Ä‡§ö‡§ï‡•ã ‡§≠‡§ø‡§®‡•ç‡§®‡§§‡§æ ‡§Ø‡•ã ‡§π‡•ã  ‡§π‡§æ‡§Æ‡•Ä ‡§µ‡§∏‡•ç‡§§‡•Å‡§π‡§∞‡•Ç ‡§™‡§∞‡§ø‡§µ‡§∞‡•ç‡§§‡§® ‡§ó‡§∞‡•ç‡§® ‡§∏‡§ï‡•ç‡§¶‡§õ‡•å‡§Ç  ‡§ú‡§¨‡§ï‡§ø ‡§™‡•ç‡§∞‡§æ‡§á‡§Æ‡§¨‡§æ‡§∞‡•Ä ‡§Æ‡§æ‡§®‡§π‡§∞‡•Ç  ‡§Ö‡§™‡§∞‡§ø‡§µ‡§∞‡•ç‡§§‡§®‡•Ä‡§Ø ‡•§
For example:
‡§â‡§¶‡§æ‡§π‡§∞‡§£ ‡§ï‡•ã ‡§≤‡§æ‡§ó‡•Ä:
let myPrimitive = "first value";
myPrimitive = "another value";
// myPrimitive now points to another string.
let myObject = { key: "first value" };
myObject.key = "another value";
// myObject points to the same object.

You can add, modify, or delete properties of an object using the dot notation or the square bracket notation.
‡§§‡§™‡§æ‡§à‡§Ç ‡§•‡§™‡•ç‡§®, ‡§™‡§∞‡§ø‡§Æ‡§æ‡§∞‡•ç‡§ú‡§®, ‡§µ‡§æ ‡§°‡§ü ‡§®‡•ã‡§ü‡•á‡§∂‡§® ‡§µ‡§æ ‡§µ‡§∞‡•ç‡§ó ‡§¨‡•ç‡§∞‡•à‡§ï‡•á‡§ü ‡§®‡•ã‡§ü ‡§™‡•ç‡§∞‡§Ø‡•ã‡§ó ‡§ó‡§∞‡•á‡§∞ ‡§µ‡§∏‡•ç‡§§‡•Å‡§ï‡•ã ‡§ó‡•Å‡§£‡§π‡§∞‡•Ç ‡§Æ‡•á‡§ü‡§æ‡§â‡§® ‡§∏‡§ï‡•ç‡§®‡•Å‡§π‡•Å‡§®‡•ç‡§õ‡•§
let object = {};
object.foo = 'bar'; // Add property 'foo'
object['baz'] = 'qux'; // Add property 'baz'
object.foo = 'quux'; // Modify property 'foo'
delete object.baz; // Delete property 'baz'

Primitive values (such as numbers and strings) are immutable, while objects (such as arrays and objects) are mutable.
‡§Ü‡§¶‡§ø‡§Æ ‡§Æ‡§æ‡§®‡§π‡§∞‡•Ç (‡§ú‡§∏‡•ç‡§§‡•à ‡§®‡§Æ‡•ç‡§¨‡§∞‡§π‡§∞‡•Ç ‡§∞ ‡§§‡§æ‡§∞‡§π‡§∞‡•Ç) ‡§Ö‡§™‡§∞‡§ø‡§µ‡§∞‡•ç‡§§‡§®‡•Ä‡§Ø ‡§õ‡§®‡•ç, ‡§ú‡§¨‡§ï‡§ø ‡§µ‡§∏‡•ç‡§§‡•Å‡§π‡§∞‡•Ç (‡§ú‡§∏‡•ç‡§§‡•à ‡§Ü‡§∞‡•ç‡§ú‡§® ‡§∞ ‡§µ‡§∏‡•ç‡§§‡•Å‡§π‡§∞‡•Ç) ‡§Æ‡•ç‡§Ø‡•Ç‡§ü ‡§ó‡§∞‡•ç‡§® ‡§Ø‡•ã‡§ó‡•ç‡§Ø ‡§õ‡§®‡•ç‡•§

objects/reference.html.body:
Reference
‡§∏‡§®‡•ç‡§¶‡§∞‡•ç‡§≠
Objects are never copied. They are passed around by reference. An object reference is a value that refers to an object. When you create an object using the new operator or object literal syntax, JavaScript creates an object and assigns a reference to it.
‡§µ‡§∏‡•ç‡§§‡•Å‡§π‡§∞‡•Ç  ‡§õ‡•à‡§®‡§®‡•ç * ‡§™‡•ç‡§∞‡§§‡§ø‡§≤‡§ø‡§™‡§ø ‡§ó‡§∞‡•ç‡§®‡•Å‡§π‡•ã‡§∏‡•ç ‡•§ ‡§§‡§ø‡§®‡•Ä‡§π‡§∞‡•Ç ‡§∏‡§®‡•ç‡§¶‡§∞‡•ç‡§≠ ‡§¶‡•ç‡§µ‡§æ‡§∞‡§æ ‡§µ‡§∞‡§ø‡§™‡§∞‡§ø ‡§™‡§æ‡§∞‡§ø‡§§ ‡§π‡•Å‡§®‡•ç‡§õ‡§®‡•ç‡•§ ‡§è‡§ï ‡§µ‡§∏‡•ç‡§§‡•Å ‡§∏‡§®‡•ç‡§¶‡§∞‡•ç‡§≠ ‡§è‡§ï ‡§Æ‡§æ‡§® ‡§π‡•ã ‡§ú‡•Å‡§® ‡§µ‡§∏‡•ç‡§§‡•Å‡§≤‡§æ‡§à ‡§ú‡§®‡§æ‡§â‡§Å‡§õ‡•§ ‡§ú‡§¨ ‡§§‡§™‡§æ‡§á‡§Å ‡§è‡§ï ‡§µ‡§∏‡•ç‡§§‡•Å ‡§∏‡§ø‡§∞‡•ç‡§ú‡§®‡§æ ‡§ó‡§∞‡•ç‡§®‡•Å‡§π‡•Å‡§®‡•ç‡§õ `‡§®‡§Ø‡§æ‡§Å" ‡§Ö‡§™‡§∞‡•á‡§ü‡§∞ ‡§µ‡§æ ‡§µ‡§∏‡•ç‡§§‡•Å ‡§∂‡§æ‡§¨‡•ç‡§¶‡§ø‡§ï ‡§∏‡§ø‡§®‡•ç‡§ü‡•ç‡§Ø‡§æ‡§ï‡•ç‡§∏ ‡§™‡•ç‡§∞‡§Ø‡•ã‡§ó ‡§ó‡§∞‡•á‡§∞ ‡§ú‡§æ‡§≠‡§æ‡§∏‡•ç‡§ï‡•ç‡§∞‡§ø‡§™‡•ç‡§ü‡§≤‡•á ‡§ï‡•Å‡§®‡•à ‡§µ‡§∏‡•ç‡§§‡•Å ‡§∏‡§ø‡§∞‡•ç‡§ú‡§®‡§æ ‡§ó‡§∞‡•ç‡§¶‡§õ ‡§∞ ‡§Ø‡§∏‡§≤‡§æ‡§à ‡§∏‡§®‡•ç‡§¶‡§∞‡•ç‡§≠‡§Æ‡§æ ‡§™‡•ç‡§∞‡§¶‡§æ‡§® ‡§ó‡§∞‡•ç‡§¶‡§õ‡•§
Here's an example of creating an object using the object literal syntax:
‡§Ø‡§π‡§æ‡§Å ‡§õ‡§µ‡§ø ‡§∂‡§æ‡§¨‡•ç‡§¶‡§ø‡§ï ‡§∏‡§ø‡§®‡•ç‡§ü‡•ç‡§Ø‡§æ‡§ï‡•ç‡§∏ ‡§™‡•ç‡§∞‡§Ø‡•ã‡§ó ‡§ó‡§∞‡•á‡§∞ ‡§µ‡§∏‡•ç‡§§‡•Å ‡§∏‡§ø‡§∞‡•ç‡§ú‡§®‡§æ ‡§ó‡§∞‡•ç‡§®‡•á ‡§è‡§ï ‡§â‡§¶‡§æ‡§π‡§∞‡§£ ‡§õ:
var object = {
  foo: 'bar'
};

Here's an example of creating an object using the new operator:
‡§Ø‡§π‡§æ‡§Å '‡§®‡§Ø‡§æ‡§Å "‡§Ö‡§™‡§∞‡•á‡§ü‡§∞ ‡§™‡•ç‡§∞‡§Ø‡•ã‡§ó ‡§ó‡§∞‡•á‡§∞ ‡§µ‡§∏‡•ç‡§§‡•Å ‡§∏‡§ø‡§∞‡•ç‡§ú‡§®‡§æ ‡§ó‡§∞‡•ç‡§®‡•á ‡§è‡§ï ‡§â‡§¶‡§æ‡§π‡§∞‡§£ ‡§õ:
var object = new Object();
object.foo = 'bar';

When you assign an object reference to a variable, the variable simply holds a reference to the object, not the object itself. This means that if you assign the object reference to another variable, both variables will point to the same object.
‡§ú‡§¨ ‡§§‡§™‡§æ‡§à‡§Ç ‡§≠‡•ç‡§Ø‡§æ‡§∞‡•Ä‡§è‡§¨‡§≤‡§≤‡§æ‡§à ‡§è‡§ï ‡§µ‡§∏‡•ç‡§§‡•Å ‡§∏‡§®‡•ç‡§¶‡§∞‡•ç‡§≠ ‡§§‡•ã‡§ï‡•ç‡§®‡•Å‡§π‡•Å‡§®‡•ç‡§õ, ‡§≠‡•ç‡§Ø‡§æ‡§∞‡•Ä‡§è‡§¨‡§≤‡§≤‡•á ‡§µ‡§∏‡•ç‡§§‡•Å‡§ï‡•ã ‡§∏‡§®‡•ç‡§¶‡§∞‡•ç‡§≠‡§Æ‡§æ ‡§∏‡§Æ‡§æ‡§µ‡•á‡§∂ ‡§ó‡§∞‡•ç‡§¶‡§õ, ‡§µ‡§∏‡•ç‡§§‡•Å ‡§®‡•à ‡§π‡•ã‡§à‡§®‡•§ ‡§Ø‡§∏‡§ï‡•ã ‡§Æ‡§§‡§≤‡§¨ ‡§Ø‡•ã ‡§π‡•ã ‡§ï‡§ø ‡§Ø‡§¶‡§ø ‡§§‡§™‡§æ‡§à‡§Ç‡§≤‡•á ‡§Ö‡§∞‡•ç‡§ï‡•ã ‡§ö‡§∞‡§≤‡§æ‡§à ‡§µ‡§∏‡•ç‡§§‡•Å ‡§∏‡§®‡•ç‡§¶‡§∞‡•ç‡§≠ ‡§®‡§ø‡§∞‡•ç‡§¶‡§ø‡§∑‡•ç‡§ü ‡§ó‡§∞‡•ç‡§®‡•Å‡§≠‡§Ø‡•ã ‡§≠‡§®‡•á, ‡§¶‡•Å‡§¨‡•à ‡§≠‡•á‡§∞‡§ø‡§è‡§¨‡§≤‡§≤‡•á ‡§â‡§π‡•Ä ‡§µ‡§∏‡•ç‡§§‡•Å‡§≤‡§æ‡§à ‡§î‡§Ç‡§≤‡•ç‡§Ø‡§æ‡§â‡§Å‡§õ‡•§
For example:
‡§â‡§¶‡§æ‡§π‡§∞‡§£ ‡§ï‡•ã ‡§≤‡§æ‡§ó‡•Ä:
var object1 = {
  foo: 'bar'
};

var object2 = object1;

console.log(object1 === object2); // Output: true

In the example above, both object1 and object2 are variables that hold references to the same object. The === operator is used to compare the references, not the objects themselves, and it returns true because both variables hold references to the same object.
‡§Æ‡§æ‡§•‡§ø‡§ï‡•ã ‡§â‡§¶‡§æ‡§π‡§∞‡§£‡§Æ‡§æ, ‡§¶‡•Å‡§¨‡•à ‡§µ‡§∏‡•ç‡§§‡•Å 1 `````````` ‡§µ‡§∏‡•ç‡§§‡•Å 2 ribles ‡§ï‡§ø ‡§∏‡§Æ‡§æ‡§® ‡§µ‡§∏‡•ç‡§§‡•Å‡§π‡§∞‡•Ç‡§Æ‡§æ ‡§∏‡§®‡•ç‡§¶‡§∞‡•ç‡§≠‡§π‡§∞‡•Ç ‡§õ‡§®‡•ç‡•§ === ‡§Ö‡§™‡§∞‡•á‡§ü‡§∞ ‡§∏‡§®‡•ç‡§¶‡§∞‡•ç‡§≠‡§π‡§∞‡•Ç ‡§§‡•Å‡§≤‡§®‡§æ ‡§ó‡§∞‡•ç‡§® ‡§™‡•ç‡§∞‡§Ø‡•ã‡§ó ‡§ó‡§∞‡§ø‡§®‡•ç‡§õ, ‡§µ‡§∏‡•ç‡§§‡•Å‡§π‡§∞‡•Ç ‡§Ü‡§´‡•à‡§Ç ‡§π‡•ã‡§á‡§®, ‡§∞ ‡§Ø‡§∏‡§≤‡•á ‡§∏‡§æ‡§Å‡§ö‡•ã "‡§∏‡•ç‡§µ‡•Ä‡§ï‡§æ‡§∞ ‡§ó‡§∞‡•ç‡§¶‡§õ ‡§ï‡§ø‡§®‡§≠‡§®‡•á ‡§¶‡•Å‡§¨‡•à ‡§≠‡•á‡§∞‡§ø‡§è‡§¨‡§≤‡§≤‡•á ‡§∏‡§Æ‡§æ‡§® ‡§µ‡§∏‡•ç‡§§‡•Å‡§Æ‡§æ ‡§∏‡§®‡•ç‡§¶‡§∞‡•ç‡§≠ ‡§ó‡§∞‡•ç‡§¶‡§õ‡•§
You can use the Object.assign() method to create a new object that is a copy of an existing object. 
