Interactions from the keyboard such as keypresses need to be constantly read to catch the key‚Äôs state before it‚Äôs released again.  Performing other time-intensive computations might cause you to miss a key press. This used to be the input handling mechanism of some primitive machines. A further step up is to use a queue, I.e. a program that periodically checks the queue for new events and reacts to it. This approach is called polling.
